{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dd9d5445-6e4b-45e2-a1ee-093c0945b398","content":"Your current file compiles fine because both arguments are already typed as `object`, so the compiler infers `T = object`. The CS1503 error happens when arguments have **different static types** (e.g., `string` vs `object`), making `T` ambiguous.\n\n**The fix:** add an explicit generic type parameter `<object>` to your assert calls:","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_JjqhUvG02qNgzsYLCxYEzo","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-b336783e99db448782252dea986e6b8c/ComparisonTests.cs","old_str":"        Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual);","new_str":"        Assert.AreEqual<object>(expected, actual);"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"edit the file at /tmp/sv-b336783e99db448782252dea986e6b8c/ComparisonTests.cs."},{"toolCallId":"tooluse_euUy3RkZSmT28MtzavvPBp","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-b336783e99db448782252dea986e6b8c/ComparisonTests.cs","old_str":"        Assert.AreNotEqual(a, b);","new_str":"        Assert.AreNotEqual<object>(a, b);"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"edit the file at /tmp/sv-b336783e99db448782252dea986e6b8c/ComparisonTests.cs."}],"interactionId":"aab3da40-1599-47cc-92f7-a2cbb8a0de61","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Interesting - the build actually succeeds with this code. MSTest 3.8.0 apparently still has the `object` overloads or the generic overloads accept `object` type inference. Let me check what version might cause the issue, or if the user's real code has mixed types (e.g., `Assert.AreEqual(\"hello\", someObject)` where one arg is `string` and the other is `object`).\n\nActually, in MSTest v3, `Assert.AreEqual<T>(T expected, T actual)` is the generic version. When both arguments are `object`, it infers `T = object` and works fine. \n\nThe problem shows up when you mix types like comparing a `string` against an `object` - that's where the ambiguity kicks in. Since this test file compiles without issues, the user's actual code must have those mixed-type comparisons causing the error. The solution is to explicitly specify the generic type parameter, like `Assert.AreEqual<object>(expected, actual)`, to resolve the ambiguity that MSTest v3 introduced.","outputTokens":841},"id":"61d1ef07-6266-4d70-bc78-58b9d639a38e","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:58:39.353Z","parentId":"05108645-0bed-4a2d-b702-1ed683bc42ba"}
