{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c8cc6c10-060a-4510-b7a6-36f04237e1dc","content":"Build succeeds. Here's what changed and why:\n\n**Root cause:** MSTest v3 replaced `Assert.AreEqual(object, object)` with the generic `Assert.AreEqual<T>(T, T)`. When the two arguments have different static types (e.g., `string` and `object`), the compiler can't infer `T` → CS1503.\n\n**Fix pattern:** Add `<object>` to disambiguate:\n\n```csharp\n// Before (fails when arg types differ)\nAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual);\n\n// After\nAssert.AreEqual<object>(expected, actual);\nAssert.AreNotEqual<object>(a, b);\n```\n\n`Assert.AreSame` wasn't affected — it still takes `object` parameters since it only checks reference identity.\n\nFor your broader codebase, search for `Assert.AreEqual(` and `Assert.AreNotEqual(` calls where the arguments have mismatched types and apply the same `<object>` fix.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"aab3da40-1599-47cc-92f7-a2cbb8a0de61","outputTokens":234},"id":"d524a54c-d7e0-4465-a0be-a617f2c957d2","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:58:52.249Z","parentId":"e8ffc007-390f-497f-b828-9f6a8570f06e"}
